<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-109-408  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 109 408.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  Feb 1990 v14 n2 p101(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Database strategies: getting the right fit. (rethinking databasedesign)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Liskin, Miriam.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Users need to re-evaluate their database periodically not only forminor upgrades or enhancements to improve the quality of the dataand the reports it produces, but also for the possibility of amajor database design overhaul.andP;  When restructuring a database,the user may decide to revise a file structure or combine files,which can become difficult if field correspondence is notone-to-one.andP;  Changing a database design can also be burdensome ifthe files are large.andP;  If a major new release of a user's databasesoftware is not totally compatible with its predecessor, thesoftware vendor often provides a utility to convert databases andother files to the new internal storage formats.andP;  Users shouldalso consider changing file structures to use any new data typesthe new software release might offer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data base management systemsUpgradingData base designData ManagementFile Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>